Citations
Date: 24/11/1847
Source: Letters to His Father, 1843-1851
Author: CHAPMAN
Vol / Page: 147
Edition:
Quote: The Wairarapa settlers are uneasy about their tenure ... At present they are the lessees of the Ngatikahunu [sic] ... The sort of contract which the squatters make with the natives is void by the Common Law, for the `Queen' is the only source of title. At Common Law therefore the lease is a mere nullity. The Courts would refuse to look at it. But by an ordinance it is now a punishable misdemeanour to deal with the natives without licence. The Wairarapa squatters must move off if the Governor choose to give them notice.
Notes: 1847 Nov 24 H.S. Chapman Letters to His Father [MS ATB] in 1958 Miller Early Victorian NZ 147

