Date: 12/4/1851
Source: Lyttelton Times
Author:
Vol / Page: 6
Edition:
Quote:  ... these large tracts of land if not let for pasturage, would either remain wholly useless or would be surreptitiously occupied by squatters in all directions, defying laws, and enjoying privileges to the detriment of the original land purchasers ... viz., pasturage without extra payment.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1853
Source: Auckland
Author: SWAINSON
Vol / Page: 129
Edition:
Quote: ... it is a rare occurrence to travel for a whole day without coming to a native settlement. Now and then, too, a solitary European squatter may be met with; and, more frequently still, a Mission station. <i>Ibid.</i>238 If he do not choose to purchase or lease land, he may become a<i> squatter</i>; that is, he may set himself down beyond the boundaries of the settlement altogether. ... In the case of squatting, it is advisable to pay a small ... tribute to the resident natives ... <i>Ibid.</i> 129 In the course of his wanderings, the [bush] traveller ... will meet settlers of every degree, from the poor isolated squatter of the interior to the owner of well-cultivated fields and numerous flocks and herds; ...
Notes: [N.I.]

Date: 0/0/1958
Source: Whitcombe's Modern Junior Dictionary (8th edn)
Author:
Vol / Page: 383
Edition:
Quote:  2. A sheepfarmer occupying a large area of land, paying a low rent for it, but not buying it.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1955
Source: NZ Contemp. Dict. Suppl. (Whitcombe's)
Author:
Vol / Page: 625
Edition:
Quote: <i>squatter n.</i> originally one wno settled on land without title or licence; now a tenant of the crown renting large areas for pasturage; any owner of large pastoral property; the bronze- wing pigeon.
Notes: [?Aust]

